automatically pick the right

00:41:09.726 --> 00:41:10.986
variant based on whether it's

00:41:10.986 --> 00:41:11.716
appearing in the light

00:41:11.716 --> 00:41:14.256
appearance or dark appearance.

00:41:14.256 --> 00:41:15.656
However, Rachel also showed us

00:41:15.656 --> 00:41:16.366
how there are a number of

00:41:16.366 --> 00:41:18.306
colorful system colors that

00:41:18.306 --> 00:41:19.456
already have these light and

00:41:19.456 --> 00:41:20.926
dark variants, which we could

00:41:20.926 --> 00:41:21.556
use instead.

00:41:22.016 --> 00:41:24.646
For instance, we could use

00:41:24.776 --> 00:41:26.416
systemRed, systemYellow, and

00:41:26.416 --> 00:41:28.806
systemGreen, which, if we return

00:41:28.806 --> 00:41:29.986
back to Chameleon Wrangler, we

00:41:29.986 --> 00:41:31.626
can see looks really great and

00:41:31.626 --> 00:41:33.596
has those buttons pop on top of

00:41:33.596 --> 00:41:34.196
that background.

00:41:35.836 --> 00:41:36.816
What's really cool about this

00:41:36.816 --> 00:41:39.086
combination is that not only do

00:41:39.086 --> 00:41:41.306
we get a very specific green

00:41:41.306 --> 00:41:42.686
color for both Light and Dark

00:41:42.686 --> 00:41:44.686
Mode, but with the content tint

00:41:44.686 --> 00:41:46.496
API, the system effects applied

00:41:46.496 --> 00:41:48.226
on top of that vary based on

00:41:48.226 --> 00:41:49.046
appearance as well.

00:41:49.926 --> 00:41:51.666
As Raymond discussed, in the

00:41:51.666 --> 00:41:52.856
light appearance, there's a

00:41:52.856 --> 00:41:54.316
darkening effect on top of that

00:41:54.316 --> 00:41:55.086
base tint color.

00:41:55.686 --> 00:41:56.436
Meanwhile, in the dark

00:41:56.436 --> 00:41:57.406
appearance, there's a

00:41:57.406 --> 00:41:58.966
brightening effect.

00:42:00.016 --> 00:42:01.776
All of these effects are further

00:42:01.776 --> 00:42:03.306
customized for the increased

00:42:03.306 --> 00:42:06.266
contrast setting without any

00:42:06.266 --> 00:42:07.566
changes from our application.

00:42:07.916 --> 00:42:09.446
So, it's really great that we

00:42:09.446 --> 00:42:11.156
didn't have to specify all 12 of

00:42:11.156 --> 00:42:11.936
these colors.

00:42:12.156 --> 00:42:13.226
And instead, we specified a

00:42:13.226 --> 00:42:14.786
single one and, thanks to

00:42:14.786 --> 00:42:16.046
dynamic system colors and

00:42:16.046 --> 00:42:17.766
dynamic system effects, we got

00:42:17.766 --> 00:42:18.936
all of this completely

00:42:18.936 --> 00:42:19.586
automatically.

00:42:21.896 --> 00:42:23.616
So, our Moodometer is looking

00:42:23.616 --> 00:42:23.956
great.

00:42:24.736 --> 00:42:25.946
Next, we can step over to

00:42:25.946 --> 00:42:27.356
another type of app where we

00:42:27.356 --> 00:42:28.646
keep track of very important

00:42:28.646 --> 00:42:30.506
information about Chloe, such as

00:42:30.506 --> 00:42:32.166
how stressed she's feeling or

00:42:32.166 --> 00:42:33.436
more importantly, what's her

00:42:33.436 --> 00:42:34.386
favorite type of berry?

00:42:35.476 --> 00:42:36.926
We can see here that this

00:42:36.926 --> 00:42:38.226
already looks great, because we

00:42:38.226 --> 00:42:40.916
are using stock Cocoa controls,

00:42:41.096 --> 00:42:42.446
which automatically adjust for

00:42:42.446 --> 00:42:43.006
Dark Mode.

00:42:44.316 --> 00:42:46.206
We can see how it reacts to the

00:42:46.266 --> 00:42:47.256
accent color feature that

00:42:47.256 --> 00:42:48.896
Raymond talked about by opening

00:42:48.896 --> 00:42:50.876
up system preferences, changing

00:42:50.876 --> 00:42:52.336
the color to a nice chameleon

00:42:52.336 --> 00:42:54.216
striped yellow, and returning

00:42:54.216 --> 00:42:55.466
back to Chameleon Wrangler.

00:42:56.596 --> 00:42:57.666
We can, again, see that the

00:42:57.666 --> 00:42:59.436
built-in controls automatically

00:42:59.436 --> 00:43:00.886
adjust to that yellow accent

00:43:00.886 --> 00:43:02.816
color, including the focus ring

00:43:02.926 --> 00:43:03.736
and highlight color.

00:43:04.986 --> 00:43:05.976
However, we can notice that our

00:43:05.976 --> 00:43:07.546
custom tab bar has remained

00:43:07.546 --> 00:43:09.146
blue, even though we've changed

00:43:09.146 --> 00:43:09.756
the accent color.

00:43:10.966 --> 00:43:12.366
Because this blue doesn't really

00:43:12.366 --> 00:43:13.636
have any significance for our

00:43:13.636 --> 00:43:15.356
application, we probably want it

00:43:15.356 --> 00:43:17.586
to be following that accent

00:43:18.576 --> 00:43:18.716
color.

00:43:18.896 --> 00:43:20.136
Like Rachel talked about, we

00:43:20.136 --> 00:43:21.876
have a few different colors that

00:43:21.876 --> 00:43:23.786
will follow the users' accent

00:43:23.786 --> 00:43:24.896
and highlight color selection.

00:43:25.876 --> 00:43:27.396
New in Mojave is a control

00:43:27.396 --> 00:43:29.186
accent color, which you can use

00:43:29.266 --> 00:43:31.166
to directly mimic the accented

00:43:31.166 --> 00:43:33.096
areas on system controls, such

00:43:33.096 --> 00:43:34.536
as the sides of popup buttons,

00:43:34.916 --> 00:43:36.386
default push buttons, or the

00:43:36.386 --> 00:43:37.706
selected segment of a segmented

00:43:37.706 --> 00:43:38.126
control.

00:43:39.616 --> 00:43:40.936
There's also selected content

00:43:40.936 --> 00:43:41.926
background color, which is what

00:43:41.926 --> 00:43:43.006
you see in the background of

00:43:43.006 --> 00:43:44.586
selected table rows, and you can

00:43:44.586 --> 00:43:45.556
use to indicate custom

00:43:45.556 --> 00:43:46.136
selection.

00:43:47.426 --> 00:43:48.486
And selected text background

00:43:48.486 --> 00:43:50.366
color is exactly what it sounds

00:43:50.366 --> 00:43:50.616
like.

00:43:51.136 --> 00:43:53.606
So, going back to our app, we

00:43:53.606 --> 00:43:54.906
can see that we're using system

00:43:54.906 --> 00:43:56.506
blue color for this custom tab

00:43:56.506 --> 00:43:58.376
selection, and, instead, we can

00:43:58.376 --> 00:43:59.696
just swap that over to using

00:43:59.696 --> 00:44:00.756
controlAccentColor.

00:44:02.676 --> 00:44:04.046
The next problem here with the

00:44:04.046 --> 00:44:05.516
tab bar is a little more subtle.

00:44:06.366 --> 00:44:07.956
If we bring our cursor over and

00:44:08.056 --> 00:44:10.046
press down on it, we can see

00:44:10.046 --> 00:44:11.086
that we're getting a darkening

00:44:11.086 --> 00:44:12.406
effect instead of the

00:44:12.406 --> 00:44:13.546
brightening effect that we

00:44:13.546 --> 00:44:14.586
should in Dark Mode.

00:44:15.846 --> 00:44:16.986
This is because we are taking

00:44:16.986 --> 00:44:18.256
that base color and just

00:44:18.256 --> 00:44:20.006
applying a constant 30%

00:44:20.006 --> 00:44:21.856
darkening effect to it, assuming

00:44:21.856 --> 00:44:23.116
that would look fine in the

00:44:23.116 --> 00:44:24.506
light appearance.

00:44:25.576 --> 00:44:27.356
Instead, we want to describe

00:44:27.356 --> 00:44:28.666
something that basically this

00:44:28.726 --> 00:44:30.976
color is being pressed, and that

00:44:30.976 --> 00:44:33.726
semantic description can carry

00:44:33.726 --> 00:44:35.316
whatever effect it needs to in

00:44:35.316 --> 00:44:36.176
the light versus dark

00:44:36.176 --> 00:44:37.416
appearance.

00:44:37.416 --> 00:44:38.596
So, with the new system effect

00:44:38.596 --> 00:44:41.546
API in Mojave on NSColor, we can

00:44:41.546 --> 00:44:42.946
describe that exact semantic.

00:44:43.836 --> 00:44:45.036
We can take our base color of

00:44:45.036 --> 00:44:46.806
controlAccentColor, say that we

00:44:46.806 --> 00:44:47.876
want to get the pressed variant,

00:44:48.076 --> 00:44:49.656
and it will react appropriately

00:44:49.746 --> 00:44:51.026
in both the light and dark

00:44:51.026 --> 00:44:52.246
appearance.

00:44:54.936 --> 00:44:56.316
There's one more area of our

00:44:56.316 --> 00:44:57.726
application where you can see

00:44:57.836 --> 00:44:59.586
the accent color, and that's in

00:44:59.586 --> 00:45:01.076
this photo browser where we draw

00:45:01.076 --> 00:45:02.406
a selection ring around the

00:45:02.406 --> 00:45:03.816
selected photo.

00:45:04.356 --> 00:45:06.126
Here, we were using the

00:45:06.226 --> 00:45:08.026
selectedContentBackgroundColor,

00:45:08.376 --> 00:45:09.576
and that, again, automatically

00:45:09.576 --> 00:45:11.066
adjusts based on the user's

00:45:11.066 --> 00:45:12.056
selected accent.

00:45:13.846 --> 00:45:14.696
Let's open up one of these

00:45:14.696 --> 00:45:15.986
photos and take a look at a

00:45:15.986 --> 00:45:17.956
nice, big, beautiful photo of

00:45:17.956 --> 00:45:18.336
Chloe.

00:45:19.056 --> 00:45:21.396
The first thing that stands out

00:45:21.396 --> 00:45:22.636
is the fact that the background

00:45:22.636 --> 00:45:24.436
has not adjusted for Dark Mode.

00:45:25.066 --> 00:45:26.276
It's still using its light

00:45:26.276 --> 00:45:28.256
translucency effect similar to a

00:45:28.256 --> 00:45:29.106
hardcoded color.

00:45:30.916 --> 00:45:32.066
This effect is provided by

00:45:32.066 --> 00:45:33.896
NSVisualEfffectView, which

00:45:33.926 --> 00:45:35.246
provides the translucent blur

00:45:35.246 --> 00:45:36.616
materials you see across the

00:45:36.616 --> 00:45:37.026
system.

00:45:37.186 --> 00:45:38.766
For instance, there's the

00:45:38.766 --> 00:45:40.236
sidebars which blur onto the

00:45:40.236 --> 00:45:41.736
desktop and other windows behind

00:45:41.736 --> 00:45:43.446
it, as well as things like the

00:45:43.446 --> 00:45:44.886
title bar, which blur the

00:45:44.886 --> 00:45:45.886
content that's scrolled

00:45:45.886 --> 00:45:47.066
underneath.

00:45:47.966 --> 00:45:50.226
NSVisualEffectView also enables

00:45:50.226 --> 00:45:51.566
the vibrant foreground blending,

00:45:51.866 --> 00:45:53.636
that Raymond talked about, by

00:45:53.636 --> 00:45:55.586
taking a grayscale color plus a

00:45:55.586 --> 00:45:57.206
Blend Mode and making it really

00:45:57.206 --> 00:45:58.846
pop on top of these backgrounds.

00:45:59.826 --> 00:46:00.906
The advanced Dark Mode talk is

00:46:00.906 --> 00:46:01.756
going to go into a lot more

00:46:01.756 --> 00:46:03.036
detail about how you can use

00:46:03.036 --> 00:46:04.366
those blend modes effectively.

00:46:06.686 --> 00:46:08.046
Turns out that a lot of places

00:46:08.046 --> 00:46:09.256
automatically get these blur

00:46:09.256 --> 00:46:10.676
materials for free.

00:46:10.856 --> 00:46:12.916
For instance, every titlebar of

00:46:12.916 --> 00:46:14.326
an NSWindow will automatically

00:46:14.326 --> 00:46:16.006
have a titlebar material showing

00:46:16.006 --> 00:46:17.706
onto the content behind it.

00:46:18.496 --> 00:46:20.156
Source list table views and

00:46:20.156 --> 00:46:21.756
sidebar style split-view items

00:46:22.046 --> 00:46:23.286
will automatically get a sidebar

00:46:23.286 --> 00:46:24.866
material showing onto the

00:46:24.866 --> 00:46:26.166
content behind the window.

00:46:26.386 --> 00:46:29.436
For custom UIs it's pretty easy

00:46:29.436 --> 00:46:30.616
to build these custom effects

00:46:30.616 --> 00:46:31.426
ourselves, as well.

00:46:32.136 --> 00:46:33.326
But the most important quality

00:46:33.326 --> 00:46:34.726
of them are the material that

00:46:34.726 --> 00:46:36.276
you choose to have them

00:46:36.276 --> 00:46:36.776
represent.

00:46:37.976 --> 00:46:39.406
We have a few nonsemantic

00:46:39.406 --> 00:46:41.256
materials, which, like hardcoded

00:46:41.256 --> 00:46:43.126
colors, just describe the exact

00:46:43.126 --> 00:46:44.536
visual quality of the material

00:46:44.916 --> 00:46:46.256
and not the intent of what

00:46:46.256 --> 00:46:47.126
you're trying to represent.

00:46:48.086 --> 00:46:49.536
These will not be adjusted for

00:46:49.536 --> 00:46:50.786
Dark Mode and will stay with

00:46:50.786 --> 00:46:51.866
that exact quality.

00:46:53.066 --> 00:46:54.106
However, we have a number of

00:46:54.106 --> 00:46:55.486
semantic materials, as well,

00:46:55.986 --> 00:46:57.346
which allow you to describe what

00:46:57.346 --> 00:46:59.126
type of UI your custom UI is

00:46:59.256 --> 00:47:00.216
intending to represent.

00:47:00.216 --> 00:47:02.226
For instance, for a custom menu

00:47:02.226 --> 00:47:03.426
like UI, you would want to use

00:47:03.466 --> 00:47:04.296
the menu material.

00:47:04.416 --> 00:47:06.196
And these not only adjust for

00:47:06.196 --> 00:47:07.976
Dark Mode, but guarantee that UI

00:47:07.976 --> 00:47:10.246
to always match those materials

00:47:10.306 --> 00:47:11.556
even when the system changes in

00:47:11.556 --> 00:47:11.986
the future.

00:47:13.156 --> 00:47:14.236
We've had a few of these in the

00:47:14.236 --> 00:47:16.646
past, but in Mojave, we have

00:47:16.646 --> 00:47:17.966
several more so that you can

00:47:17.966 --> 00:47:19.346
make sure to really tailor your

00:47:19.346 --> 00:47:21.496
custom UI to match the material

00:47:21.596 --> 00:47:24.936
it needs to.

00:47:25.176 --> 00:47:26.506
Jumping back to our photo here,

00:47:26.506 --> 00:47:27.516
we can see that we were using

00:47:27.516 --> 00:47:28.706
the mediumLight material,

00:47:29.046 --> 00:47:29.776
because we were trying to

00:47:29.776 --> 00:47:31.496
represent Quick Look style

00:47:31.496 --> 00:47:32.426
popover windows.

00:47:33.126 --> 00:47:34.296
And instead, we can just simply

00:47:34.296 --> 00:47:35.556
swap that over to the popover

00:47:35.556 --> 00:47:37.206
material and get the exact

00:47:37.206 --> 00:47:41.046
effect we want to in Dark Mode.

00:47:41.266 --> 00:47:42.856
Now, this isn't the only area

00:47:42.856 --> 00:47:45.076
where we get a unique material

00:47:45.076 --> 00:47:46.366
showing in the background of our

00:47:46.366 --> 00:47:46.516
UI.

00:47:46.516 --> 00:47:48.666
Like Raymond talked about,

00:47:48.966 --> 00:47:50.146
there's this desktop tinting

00:47:50.146 --> 00:47:51.596
effect that's shown here in the

00:47:51.596 --> 00:47:52.916
background of our photo gallery.

00:47:53.436 --> 00:47:54.306
We're getting a little bit of

00:47:54.306 --> 00:47:55.396
that blue from that desktop

00:47:55.396 --> 00:47:57.146
behind it, creating this really

00:47:57.146 --> 00:47:58.486
visually harmonious result.

00:47:59.516 --> 00:48:00.836
It's a lot easier to see on top

00:48:00.836 --> 00:48:02.066
of a more vibrant background,

00:48:02.206 --> 00:48:03.686
such as these beautiful flower

00:48:03.686 --> 00:48:04.236
pictures.

00:48:06.316 --> 00:48:08.626
There's three different variants

00:48:08.956 --> 00:48:10.806
that have semantics with these

00:48:10.806 --> 00:48:11.866
background materials.

00:48:12.356 --> 00:48:13.436
There's the window backgrounds

00:48:13.436 --> 00:48:14.616
that we see on the backgrounds

00:48:14.616 --> 00:48:16.596
of generic windows; Under Page

00:48:16.596 --> 00:48:18.456
Background, which appears behind

00:48:18.456 --> 00:48:19.676
document areas such as in

00:48:19.676 --> 00:48:20.906
Preview or Keynote.

00:48:21.516 --> 00:48:23.726
And perhaps most commonly is the

00:48:23.726 --> 00:48:25.146
Content Background material,

00:48:25.726 --> 00:48:26.656
which is white in light

00:48:26.656 --> 00:48:28.306
appearance and, of course, dark

00:48:28.306 --> 00:48:29.206
in the dark appearance.

00:48:30.166 --> 00:48:31.216
In fact, all of these are now

00:48:31.216 --> 00:48:32.676
dark in the dark appearance but

00:48:32.676 --> 00:48:34.306
also have that wallpaper tinting

00:48:34.366 --> 00:48:36.866
effect.

00:48:36.866 --> 00:48:37.766
The great news is that it's

00:48:37.816 --> 00:48:38.956
really not hard to get these

00:48:38.956 --> 00:48:39.546
effects.

00:48:39.776 --> 00:48:41.086
For the most part, it comes

00:48:41.086 --> 00:48:42.396
completely automatically by

00:48:42.396 --> 00:48:43.496
using system views.

00:48:43.496 --> 00:48:45.076
For instance, the default

00:48:45.076 --> 00:48:47.016
backgrounds of every window has

00:48:47.016 --> 00:48:48.396
that window background material

00:48:48.556 --> 00:48:49.116
built right in.

00:48:50.316 --> 00:48:52.336
In addition, [inaudible] views

00:48:52.336 --> 00:48:54.946
such as NSCollectionView or

00:48:54.946 --> 00:48:57.016
NSTableView also automatically

00:48:57.016 --> 00:48:58.246
come with the content background

00:48:58.246 --> 00:48:59.516
material built right in.

00:49:00.776 --> 00:49:01.776
We've seen a number of places

00:49:01.776 --> 00:49:02.826
across this system that were

00:49:02.826 --> 00:49:04.196
actually able to improve their

00:49:04.196 --> 00:49:05.996
Dark Mode support by deleting an

00:49:05.996 --> 00:49:07.916
override of these default colors

00:49:08.296 --> 00:49:09.186
that these views have.

00:49:10.486 --> 00:49:12.546
If you want to customize beyond

00:49:12.606 --> 00:49:13.816
the default color that these

00:49:13.816 --> 00:49:15.666
views have, you can explicitly

00:49:15.666 --> 00:49:17.556
set a variety of system colors

00:49:17.626 --> 00:49:19.346
as their background color to get

00:49:19.346 --> 00:49:20.926
the exact material effect you

00:49:20.926 --> 00:49:21.216
want.

00:49:22.916 --> 00:49:24.446
One really important note here,

00:49:24.446 --> 00:49:25.986
though, is that if you were to

00:49:25.986 --> 00:49:27.396
read the RGB values of these

00:49:27.396 --> 00:49:29.166
colors, they would not include

00:49:29.166 --> 00:49:29.946
the desktop tint.

00:49:30.836 --> 00:49:31.796
This is because, as Raymond

00:49:31.796 --> 00:49:32.816
mentioned, this tint is

00:49:32.816 --> 00:49:33.876
extremely dynamic.

00:49:34.306 --> 00:49:35.606
As you move your window around

00:49:35.606 --> 00:49:36.956
on screen, that's getting

00:49:36.956 --> 00:49:38.596
updated asynchronously to the

00:49:38.596 --> 00:49:40.576
applications rendering itself,

00:49:40.576 --> 00:49:41.536
creating a really nice

00:49:41.536 --> 00:49:43.456
experience as the user is moving

00:49:43.456 --> 00:49:44.336
around windows.

00:49:45.556 --> 00:49:46.886
So, jumping back to Chameleon

00:49:46.886 --> 00:49:48.396
Wrangler, we automatically got

00:49:48.396 --> 00:49:49.976
this content background because

00:49:49.976 --> 00:49:51.226
we just use a stock

00:49:51.226 --> 00:49:52.006
NSCollectionView.

00:49:53.456 --> 00:49:55.006
In the vital section, we got

00:49:55.006 --> 00:49:56.196
that window background material

00:49:56.196 --> 00:49:57.466
showing through because we had

00:49:57.466 --> 00:49:58.996
nothing opaque covering it up.

00:50:00.186 --> 00:50:02.006
However, in our notes section,

00:50:02.326 --> 00:50:03.296
where we have this awesome

00:50:03.296 --> 00:50:05.836
custom stationary, we have a

00:50:05.836 --> 00:50:07.426
light grey background that isn't

00:50:07.426 --> 00:50:08.456
appropriate for Dark Mode and

00:50:08.456 --> 00:50:10.016
hasn't been adjusted with that

00:50:10.016 --> 00:50:11.096
under page semantic.

00:50:11.576 --> 00:50:14.366
We can open up Interface Builder

00:50:14.366 --> 00:50:15.436
and see where we're setting up

00:50:15.436 --> 00:50:17.056
this background drawing view and

00:50:17.056 --> 00:50:18.756
see that, indeed, we are filing

00:50:18.756 --> 00:50:19.976
it with a custom gray color.

00:50:21.006 --> 00:50:23.356
And pretty quickly in IB, we can

00:50:23.356 --> 00:50:24.486
change that to using the Under

00:50:24.486 --> 00:50:25.986
Page Background color that

00:50:25.986 --> 00:50:27.626
represents that semantic and

00:50:27.626 --> 00:50:28.626
immediately see that we'll get

00:50:28.626 --> 00:50:30.696
the right result, making it look

00:50:31.116 --> 00:50:32.286
just at home with the rest of

00:50:32.286 --> 00:50:34.646
the document apps in Dark Mode.

00:50:34.646 --> 00:50:37.516
The next thing that kind of

00:50:37.516 --> 00:50:38.636
stands out here, though, is the

00:50:38.636 --> 00:50:40.156
dark foreground on top of light

00:50:40.156 --> 00:50:42.376
background of our stationary and

00:50:42.376 --> 00:50:43.036
document area.

00:50:43.036 --> 00:50:45.276
And because this is a WYSIWYG

00:50:45.276 --> 00:50:47.206
editor where we, as users of

00:50:47.336 --> 00:50:48.676
Chameleon Wrangler have complete

00:50:48.676 --> 00:50:51.276
control over the colors, images,

00:50:51.276 --> 00:50:53.876
and fonts seen within it, we

00:50:53.876 --> 00:50:55.846
expect this to stay the same as

00:50:55.846 --> 00:50:57.356
a light appearing document.

00:50:58.566 --> 00:50:59.656
However, there are a few subtle

00:50:59.656 --> 00:51:01.406
details that don't seem quite

00:51:01.406 --> 00:51:01.696
right.

00:51:01.696 --> 00:51:04.026
For instance, the text highlight

00:51:04.026 --> 00:51:05.436
color is still getting the dark

00:51:05.436 --> 00:51:07.266
variant of the text highlights,

00:51:07.266 --> 00:51:08.546
as well as the autocorrect

00:51:08.546 --> 00:51:09.846
bubbles have the dark

00:51:09.846 --> 00:51:11.376
appearance, which really clashes

00:51:11.376 --> 00:51:12.396
with the light appearance of our

00:51:12.396 --> 00:51:12.866
document.

00:51:13.986 --> 00:51:15.186
We, basically, want to have

00:51:15.186 --> 00:51:16.776
everything in this area revert

00:51:16.776 --> 00:51:18.646
back to the light appearance,

00:51:19.146 --> 00:51:20.696
and we can do that using

00:51:20.756 --> 00:51:22.066
NSAppearance.

00:51:22.406 --> 00:51:23.636
It turns out that NSAppearance

00:51:23.636 --> 00:51:24.636
is what's been providing the

00:51:24.636 --> 00:51:26.466
magic of having light versus

00:51:26.466 --> 00:51:27.786
dark variance automatically

00:51:27.786 --> 00:51:29.306
switch in Dark Mode this whole

00:51:29.306 --> 00:51:29.646
time.

00:51:30.806 --> 00:51:31.746
You can conceptualize

00:51:31.746 --> 00:51:33.396
NSAppearance as a little bundle

00:51:33.816 --> 00:51:35.526
containing all of the colors,

00:51:35.756 --> 00:51:39.176
materials, images, and control

00:51:39.176 --> 00:51:40.486
artwork that you see across the

00:51:40.486 --> 00:51:41.026
system.

00:51:41.626 --> 00:51:44.176
Now, when your application does

00:51:44.176 --> 00:51:45.586
something like request to draw

00:51:45.586 --> 00:51:47.296
with labelColor, what that does

00:51:47.296 --> 00:51:48.476
is it looks up in the current

00:51:48.476 --> 00:51:50.016
appearance for what the exact

00:51:50.016 --> 00:51:51.166
RGB values should be.

00:51:52.176 --> 00:51:53.526
The same is true for control

00:51:53.526 --> 00:51:54.696
artwork or the different

00:51:54.696 --> 00:51:56.266
material effects.

00:51:56.826 --> 00:51:58.996
Now, what's new in Mojave is the

00:51:58.996 --> 00:52:00.546
dark appearance, which our

00:52:00.546 --> 00:52:01.876
designers have meticulously

00:52:01.876 --> 00:52:03.976
crafted with redefining

00:52:03.976 --> 00:52:05.406
everything across the system.

00:52:06.926 --> 00:52:07.886
When the system is running in

00:52:07.886 --> 00:52:09.416
Dark Mode, what happens is that

00:52:09.416 --> 00:52:10.586
the dark appearance gets applied

00:52:10.586 --> 00:52:11.916
to your application instead of

00:52:11.916 --> 00:52:13.306
the light appearance.

00:52:13.406 --> 00:52:14.776
So, when labelColor goes to draw

00:52:14.776 --> 00:52:16.376
itself, it references the dark

00:52:16.376 --> 00:52:18.036
appearance as white value

00:52:18.076 --> 00:52:19.146
instead of the light appearance

00:52:19.146 --> 00:52:19.866
as darker value.

00:52:20.716 --> 00:52:21.666
The same is true for all of

00:52:21.666 --> 00:52:22.526
those materials.

00:52:23.006 --> 00:52:24.916
And these aren't the only

00:52:25.006 --> 00:52:26.376
materials in the system.

00:52:26.376 --> 00:52:27.856
Right, these aren't the only

00:52:27.856 --> 00:52:28.836
appearances in the system.

00:52:29.296 --> 00:52:30.466
There are also the high contrast

00:52:30.466 --> 00:52:32.216
appearances, which get used when

00:52:32.216 --> 00:52:33.486
the accessibility high contrast

00:52:33.486 --> 00:52:35.046
setting is turned on, these will

00:52:35.046 --> 00:52:36.266
get applied to your application

00:52:36.266 --> 00:52:36.666
instead.

00:52:36.726 --> 00:52:38.906
And there's actually even more.

00:52:39.316 --> 00:52:40.026
There are the vibrant

00:52:40.026 --> 00:52:40.976
appearances that, again,

00:52:40.976 --> 00:52:42.366
completely redefine all of these

00:52:42.366 --> 00:52:44.536
colors that appear in sidebars

00:52:44.536 --> 00:52:45.416
and titlebars.

00:52:45.946 --> 00:52:48.046
And the advanced Dark Mode talk

00:52:48.046 --> 00:52:49.106
is going to go into more detail

00:52:49.106 --> 00:52:50.156
about how you can effectively

00:52:50.156 --> 00:52:51.746
use the assets that come out of

00:52:51.746 --> 00:52:53.216
those vibrant appearances to

00:52:53.216 --> 00:52:54.336
really make them stand out.

00:52:55.986 --> 00:52:59.706
Now, by default, the appearance

00:52:59.706 --> 00:53:01.196
of your application will follow

00:53:01.196 --> 00:53:01.686
the system.

00:53:02.336 --> 00:53:03.386
However, you can explicitly

00:53:03.386 --> 00:53:04.536
override it by setting the

00:53:04.536 --> 00:53:05.706
appearance property to whatever

00:53:05.706 --> 00:53:06.076
you want.

00:53:06.496 --> 00:53:08.196
So, here we have Chameleon

00:53:08.196 --> 00:53:09.496
Wrangler in Light and Dark Mode,

00:53:10.306 --> 00:53:11.536
and we can see it's following

00:53:11.536 --> 00:53:12.956
the system, but as soon as we

00:53:12.956 --> 00:53:14.066
set its appearance to always be

00:53:14.066 --> 00:53:15.716
darkAqua, we can see it's always

00:53:15.716 --> 00:53:16.876
getting that dark appearance.

00:53:17.716 --> 00:53:19.326
The inverse is true by setting

00:53:19.326 --> 00:53:21.266
the explicitly light appearance,

00:53:21.266 --> 00:53:22.246
and, of course, setting it back

00:53:22.246 --> 00:53:23.756
to nil will have it return back

00:53:23.756 --> 00:53:25.126
to the default behavior of

00:53:25.126 --> 00:53:25.926
following the system.

00:53:27.746 --> 00:53:28.996
Now, we know that after a lot of

00:53:29.036 --> 00:53:30.766
you see your apps running in

00:53:30.766 --> 00:53:32.296
Dark Mode, you're going to be

00:53:32.296 --> 00:53:33.916
really tempted to have your app

00:53:34.216 --> 00:53:35.466
always be dark, because it's

00:53:35.466 --> 00:53:36.446
just going to look so good.

00:53:37.586 --> 00:53:39.246
But like Raymond mentioned, it's

00:53:39.246 --> 00:53:40.666
really important to keep in mind

00:53:40.666 --> 00:53:42.136
"When it is appropriate to have

00:53:42.136 --> 00:53:43.686
an always dark app?"

00:53:44.336 --> 00:53:45.586
This should be generally

00:53:45.586 --> 00:53:47.326
reserved for very media focused

00:53:47.326 --> 00:53:49.036
apps like QuickTime player or

00:53:49.036 --> 00:53:50.446
professional color-sensitive

00:53:50.446 --> 00:53:51.766
workflow apps, where it's

00:53:51.766 --> 00:53:53.146
important to eliminate all of

00:53:53.146 --> 00:53:54.546
the light behind the content.

00:53:55.586 --> 00:53:56.476
And, in general, it should be

00:53:56.476 --> 00:53:57.916
left up to a choice for the

00:53:57.916 --> 00:53:58.356
user.

00:53:59.546 --> 00:54:00.536
So, in general, this is the

00:54:00.536 --> 00:54:01.506
system preference.

00:54:01.716 --> 00:54:02.926
Some of you maybe already have a

00:54:02.926 --> 00:54:04.086
dark theme for your application

00:54:04.086 --> 00:54:05.476
controlled via app preference,

00:54:05.526 --> 00:54:06.796
so your first step would be to

00:54:06.876 --> 00:54:07.916
tie that back to the system

00:54:07.916 --> 00:54:10.156
preference so the people using

00:54:10.156 --> 00:54:11.426
the system can have a consistent

00:54:11.426 --> 00:54:12.786
experience.

00:54:13.366 --> 00:54:15.056
And in some ambiguous cases like

00:54:15.056 --> 00:54:16.286
Raymond mentioned, there may be

00:54:16.286 --> 00:54:17.356
some additional need for an

00:54:17.356 --> 00:54:18.566
in-app preference, such as in

00:54:18.566 --> 00:54:20.296
the mail case, but for the most

00:54:20.296 --> 00:54:21.606
part, the system preference

00:54:21.606 --> 00:54:23.456
should be exactly what users go

00:54:23.456 --> 00:54:23.706
for.

00:54:23.706 --> 00:54:26.466
If you do decide you need to

00:54:26.516 --> 00:54:27.876
have an always dark application,

00:54:28.096 --> 00:54:29.276
it's really important to not to

00:54:29.276 --> 00:54:30.486
use the Vibrant Dark appearance

00:54:30.486 --> 00:54:31.926
on the entire window, because

00:54:31.926 --> 00:54:33.196
that's not appropriate for the

00:54:33.196 --> 00:54:35.416
opaque window areas of the

00:54:35.416 --> 00:54:37.136
application and are really only

00:54:37.136 --> 00:54:38.266
intended for sidebars.

00:54:39.316 --> 00:54:40.226
Instead, you want to use the

00:54:40.226 --> 00:54:41.866
Dark Aqua appearance if you want

00:54:41.866 --> 00:54:43.746
to have that always dark look.

00:54:44.596 --> 00:54:46.096
In addition to be able to be set

00:54:46.096 --> 00:54:47.626
on the window as a whole, you

00:54:47.626 --> 00:54:49.046
can also set it on an individual

00:54:49.046 --> 00:54:50.276
window or view scoping, and

00:54:50.626 --> 00:54:51.826
that's inherited by all of the

00:54:51.866 --> 00:54:52.856
views contained within it.

00:54:53.626 --> 00:54:55.086
For instance, here, we're

00:54:55.086 --> 00:54:56.506
setting the sidebar to always

00:54:56.506 --> 00:54:58.736
have the darkAqua appearance if

00:54:58.736 --> 00:54:59.506
we want to experiment with

00:54:59.506 --> 00:55:00.176
something like that.

00:55:00.596 --> 00:55:01.966
And all of the text and images

00:55:01.966 --> 00:55:03.646
within that also get that dark

00:55:03.646 --> 00:55:05.946
styling, but we can also use

00:55:05.946 --> 00:55:07.356
this to fix the problem we had

00:55:07.356 --> 00:55:08.916
before with our text area.

00:55:09.876 --> 00:55:11.786
We can see here that we actually

00:55:11.786 --> 00:55:13.316
want this entire document area

00:55:13.386 --> 00:55:14.486
to remain having a light

00:55:14.486 --> 00:55:16.086
appearance, and so by setting

00:55:16.086 --> 00:55:17.536
the lightAqua appearance, we can

00:55:17.536 --> 00:55:18.406
make sure that the text

00:55:18.406 --> 00:55:19.826
highlighting color gets the

00:55:19.826 --> 00:55:21.426
correct appearance as well as

00:55:21.426 --> 00:55:22.466
the autocorrect bubble

00:55:22.676 --> 00:55:24.196
inheriting that light appearance

00:55:24.196 --> 00:55:24.556
as well.

00:55:26.606 --> 00:55:27.546
However, in addition to be able

00:55:27.546 --> 00:55:28.756
to be used for some really cool

00:55:28.756 --> 00:55:30.426
effects, it can also lead to

00:55:30.426 --> 00:55:31.966
some hard-to-debug situations.

00:55:31.966 --> 00:55:34.386
For instance, here, we're using

00:55:34.386 --> 00:55:35.336
the vibrantLight appearance

00:55:35.336 --> 00:55:36.656
explicitly on our table view,

00:55:36.656 --> 00:55:38.546
and that looks perfectly fine in

00:55:38.546 --> 00:55:39.786
the light appearance, where it's

00:55:39.786 --> 00:55:41.366
actually already inheriting the

00:55:41.366 --> 00:55:43.546
vibrantLight appearance.

00:55:43.546 --> 00:55:44.806
In Dark Mode, this quickly

00:55:44.806 --> 00:55:46.586
becomes a very visible problem.

00:55:47.226 --> 00:55:48.426
We can see that the text and

00:55:48.426 --> 00:55:49.866
images inside that table view

00:55:49.866 --> 00:55:50.876
are now inheriting that

00:55:50.876 --> 00:55:52.636
vibrantLight appearance and look

00:55:52.636 --> 00:55:53.936
bad on top of that dark

00:55:53.936 --> 00:55:54.356
background.

00:55:54.356 --> 00:55:56.386
So, for the most part, we just

00:55:56.386 --> 00:55:57.516
want to remove these explicit

00:55:57.516 --> 00:55:59.126
overrides in places where we

00:55:59.186 --> 00:56:00.776
really do not intend to have an

00:56:00.776 --> 00:56:01.986
always light appearance.

00:56:03.426 --> 00:56:04.416
This can also happen in

00:56:04.416 --> 00:56:06.116
Interface Builder, where, at the

00:56:06.116 --> 00:56:07.606
very bottom of the Attributes

00:56:07.606 --> 00:56:09.196
Inspector, we've accidentally

00:56:09.196 --> 00:56:11.006
overridden the appearance for

00:56:11.156 --> 00:56:12.656
our outline view to always be

00:56:12.656 --> 00:56:14.696
the light Aqua appearance.

00:56:14.696 --> 00:56:15.856
Here, the fix is simply to

00:56:15.856 --> 00:56:18.796
change it back to the inherited

00:56:18.796 --> 00:56:20.196
style so that it can make sure

00:56:20.196 --> 00:56:21.786
to follow Dark Mode when that's

00:56:21.786 --> 00:56:23.786
turned on, so do be sure to

00:56:23.786 --> 00:56:24.736
check for all of those.

00:56:26.176 --> 00:56:28.476
At this point, Chameleon

00:56:28.476 --> 00:56:29.956
Wrangler's looking really great

00:56:29.956 --> 00:56:30.686
in Dark Mode.

00:56:31.896 --> 00:56:33.226
But kind of an understated thing

00:56:33.226 --> 00:56:35.546
here is that, at this point,

00:56:35.686 --> 00:56:37.366
we've written 0 lines of code

00:56:37.566 --> 00:56:38.876
specific to Dark Mode.

00:56:40.116 --> 00:56:41.436
The types of changes necessary

00:56:41.436 --> 00:56:42.556
for being a great Dark Mode

00:56:42.556 --> 00:56:44.706
citizen is that you need to make

00:56:44.706 --> 00:56:46.756
sure to express the ideas

00:56:46.756 --> 00:56:48.556
semantically rather than

00:56:48.556 --> 00:56:49.006
literally.

00:56:49.306 --> 00:56:52.926
So, for instance, these same

00:56:52.926 --> 00:56:54.156
sets of changes allowed our

00:56:54.156 --> 00:56:56.686
application to not only look

00:56:56.746 --> 00:56:58.966
great in Dark Mode but also in

00:56:58.966 --> 00:57:00.386
the light appearance.

00:57:00.786 --> 00:57:01.976
Adding support for things like

00:57:01.976 --> 00:57:03.416
the accent color as well as

00:57:03.416 --> 00:57:04.616
making our label colors more

00:57:04.616 --> 00:57:05.756
consistent with the rest of the

00:57:05.756 --> 00:57:06.146
system.

00:57:07.436 --> 00:57:09.246
Further, these same sets of

00:57:09.246 --> 00:57:11.196
changes needed to be great in

00:57:11.196 --> 00:57:13.446
Dark Mode are also the same sets

00:57:13.446 --> 00:57:15.146
of changes needed to have great

00:57:15.146 --> 00:57:16.906
support for the high contrast

00:57:17.066 --> 00:57:18.056
accessibility setting.

00:57:18.146 --> 00:57:20.916
So, to reiterate what those

00:57:20.916 --> 00:57:22.436
steps were, the first and

00:57:22.436 --> 00:57:24.166
foremost was linking on the

00:57:24.166 --> 00:57:27.636
10.14 SDK using Xcode 10.

00:57:27.636 --> 00:57:29.536
For a handful of apps that

00:57:29.536 --> 00:57:30.966
already use system controls and

00:57:30.966 --> 00:57:32.986
system colors, this is the only

00:57:32.986 --> 00:57:34.026
step that's going to be needed,

00:57:34.166 --> 00:57:35.476
and it's already going to look

00:57:35.476 --> 00:57:36.306
great in Dark Mode.

00:57:36.846 --> 00:57:38.646
For the rest of us, the next

00:57:38.646 --> 00:57:40.536
step is to audit our app for the

00:57:40.536 --> 00:57:42.056
use of static colors,

00:57:42.736 --> 00:57:44.506
non-template images, and

00:57:44.666 --> 00:57:46.376
nonsemantic materials, and

00:57:46.376 --> 00:57:47.526
replace those as appropriate.

00:57:47.526 --> 00:57:49.396
For instance, this might be

00:57:49.396 --> 00:57:51.276
using a system color, a semantic

00:57:51.276 --> 00:57:53.216
material, or, in some cases,

00:57:53.216 --> 00:57:54.686
defining a custom asset catalog

00:57:54.686 --> 00:57:55.686
color or image.

00:57:56.506 --> 00:57:57.416
And, again, it's important to

00:57:57.416 --> 00:57:58.326
keep an eye out for those

00:57:58.326 --> 00:58:00.216
accidental appearance overrides.

00:58:01.676 --> 00:58:02.676
The advanced Dark Mode talk is

00:58:02.676 --> 00:58:03.636
going to go into a lot more

00:58:03.636 --> 00:58:05.606
detail here, including how to

00:58:05.926 --> 00:58:07.636
correctly use NSAppearance, how

00:58:07.636 --> 00:58:09.376
to do custom drawing and effects

00:58:09.456 --> 00:58:11.426
within NSVisualEffectView, how

00:58:11.426 --> 00:58:12.526
to make sure all of the myriad

00:58:12.526 --> 00:58:13.716
of ways you might be drawing

00:58:13.716 --> 00:58:15.526
custom views work correctly in

00:58:15.526 --> 00:58:15.996
Dark Mode.

00:58:16.386 --> 00:58:19.076
Some tips and tricks for using

